#compdef telly
# =============================================================================
# telly — TellyTV Inc.'s "An IPTV proxy" — a Go HTTP proxy that
#         takes IPTV M3U playlists + XMLTV electronic-program-
#         guides + exposes them as a virtual HDHomeRun network
#         tuner that Plex / Emby / Jellyfin / Channels DVR /
#         NextPVR / etc. can consume as if they were physical
#         OTA antenna tuners.  Distinguishing from xTeVe,
#         M3U2HDHR, Threadfin (telly's spiritual successor),
#         and other IPTV→HDHomeRun bridges by:
#           - SSDP-DISCOVERED HDHomeRun EMULATION: telly
#             advertises itself on the local network via SSDP
#             with HDHomeRun device-discovery metadata
#             (manufacturer, model number, firmware version,
#             device-id, friendly name); Plex/Emby/Jellyfin
#             auto-detect it as a tuner
#           - M3U PLAYLIST INGESTION via iptv.playlist —
#             accepts local file path OR URL; supports
#             #EXTM3U / #EXTINF playlist format universally
#           - REGEX-BASED CHANNEL FILTERING: filter.regex +
#             filter.regex-inclusive control whether the
#             provided regex INCLUDES or EXCLUDES matching
#             channels from the exposed lineup
#           - XMLTV EPG SUPPORT — telly accepts XMLTV files
#             for electronic-program-guide integration; channel
#             numbers can be inherited from XMLTV
#           - CONCURRENT STREAM LIMITING — iptv.streams flag
#             caps the number of simultaneous streams to
#             accommodate provider terms-of-service limits
#           - REVERSE-PROXY-AWARE: web.listen-address vs
#             web.base-address split — telly listens internally
#             on listen-address but advertises base-address
#             via discovery, supporting deployment behind
#             nginx/Caddy/Cloudflare reverse proxies
#           - DEEP VIPER CONFIGURATION — every flag has an env-
#             var equivalent (TELLY_*) AND can be set in a
#             telly.config YAML/TOML/JSON file; viper auto-
#             searches ./telly.config + $HOME/.telly/ + /etc/
#             telly/ for the config file
#         Used by: cord-cutters running PVR software (Plex
#         DVR / Emby Live TV / Jellyfin Live TV / Channels
#         DVR), IPTV service subscribers wanting to integrate
#         with their existing media server's tuner workflow,
#         and as a reference implementation of viper-based
#         multi-source Go configuration.
#
# Author:  TellyTV Inc. organization (tellytv on GitHub) —
#          IPTV-focused open-source group.  Original release
#          2018; community-maintained through periodic releases
#          with multiple contributors.  License: MIT.
# Source:  https://github.com/tellytv/telly
#          https://github.com/tellytv/telly/blob/master/main.go
# CLI:     main.go — uses spf13/pflag (cobra/viper-compatible
#          pflag) for flag parsing + viper.BindPFlags for
#          binding flags to viper config keys.  Headline
#          library: **spf13/viper** (pflag is cobra-companion
#          and well-documented; viper is the new variant being
#          documented here, expanding Axis 13 into Go).
# Library: github.com/spf13/viper
#          ("viper" — Steve Francia (spf13 on GitHub, also
#           author of cobra + hugo + pflag) — released 2014 as
#           "Go configuration with fangs".  Distinct from
#           every previously-documented Go library by being
#           the dominant Go layered configuration library +
#           direct cross-language parallel to Rust's config-rs
#           (R629 Axis 13 opener):
#             1. 7+ FILE FORMAT BACKENDS — TOML, YAML, JSON,
#                HCL (HashiCorp Config Language), INI, envfile
#                (.env), Java properties, with auto-detection
#                via file extension
#             2. ENVIRONMENT-VARIABLE BINDING via viper.
#                AutomaticEnv() + viper.SetEnvPrefix("APP") +
#                viper.SetEnvKeyReplacer(strings.NewReplacer(
#                ".", "_")) — automatically maps env-vars to
#                dotted config keys (TELLY_LOG_LEVEL →
#                log.level)
#             3. SEARCH-PATH HIERARCHY via viper.AddConfigPath
#                (multiple times) — viper walks paths in order
#                looking for the named config file:
#                  viper.AddConfigPath("/etc/myapp/")
#                  viper.AddConfigPath("$HOME/.myapp")
#                  viper.AddConfigPath(".")
#             4. PFLAG INTEGRATION via viper.BindPFlags +
#                viper.BindPFlag — auto-binds CLI flags
#                (parsed by spf13/pflag) to viper config keys
#                so CLI overrides take precedence over file
#                values
#             5. VALUE-PRIORITY ORDER (documented in viper
#                README):
#                  1. explicit call to Set
#                  2. flag (via pflag)
#                  3. env var
#                  4. config file
#                  5. key/value store (etcd/consul)
#                  6. default
#             6. REMOTE KEY-VALUE STORE INTEGRATION — viper
#                can pull config from etcd / consul / Firestore
#                via viper.AddRemoteProvider(...)
#             7. CONFIG WATCHING + HOT RELOAD — viper.
#                WatchConfig() reloads on file changes;
#                viper.OnConfigChange(func) hook for change
#                notifications
#             8. STEVE FRANCIA TRINITY — pflag (flag parsing) +
#                cobra (subcommand framework) + viper (config
#                loading) form the foundation of Hugo, kubectl,
#                Helm, Istio, etcd, OpenShift, GitHub CLI, and
#                thousands of other major Go applications)
# License: MIT (telly); MIT (viper)
# Status:  telly — 823+ stars on tellytv/telly, popular cord-
#          cutter IPTV tool; viper — 30,276+ stars on
#          spf13/viper (TOP-25 Go GitHub project), ~600M
#          go.sum downloads, foundational dependency of Hugo
#          + kubectl + Helm + Istio + etcd + OpenShift + GitHub
#          CLI + Cobra-based CLIs + tellytv/telly (THIS) +
#          digitalocean/doctl + konstructio/kubefirst +
#          irccloud/irccat + tens of thousands of Go
#          applications using spf13's pflag/cobra/viper trinity.
